			</td>
			
			
			<td class="BoardRowA" colspan=2 width="83%"><span style="font-weight: bold;">Date Posted:</span> 
			6/12/01 9:55am 
			<span style="font-weight: bold;">Subject:</span> Conflicting Approaches.			
			</td>
		</tr>
		<tr valign=top>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=2 width="83%">
				I see a major conflict arising, not between good/neutral/evil, but between two types of people who have chosen to play this server.  <br>  <br> The first approach is the pvp first approach. This is the approach taken by the majority of ex VZ/TZ players. Basicaly, these people believe that members of the other two teams should be attacked no questions asked. They believe that this is how it should be since it is how the server was set up. They can often be heard commenting on how crossteaming ruined there old server before shouting the cliche, STFU bloob. <br>  <br> The second approach is the roleplay first approach. This is the approach taken by the majority of ex non pvp server players. These players see this server as a last chance to roleplay, a chance to escape the mundane levelquest of blue servers. These players if roleplaying good characters, do not believe they should attack neutral on site. After all, if you are roleplaying a paladin it does not make sense to attack people just because they are neutral. Many of these people have taken to leveling and all but completely ignoring most pvp battles. <br>  <br> Myself, being from Rallos Zek can see that both these playstyles are valid. The problem is that they conflict with one another. I think if the server was just GvE as it should have been (in my opinion) that this problem would have been too small too mention. It is likely too late for this though. What do other people think? Is there a solution to this? Maybe a big roleplay event when the server opens that justifies open conflict between good and neutral? <br>  <br>  <br> P.S. My personal beliefs on this is, just because you can attack someone doesn't mean you have to. Having the option to attack though, means everything.		

			</td>
		</tr>
